## Voice / Screen reader

_Confidence: high._

> Checkbox is a single focus stop with the role "checkbox". The visible Label merges into the checkbox's accessible name and the optional Helper text merges into its description — neither is a separate focus stop. The control is tri-state: aria-checked reflects "true" (Checked), "false" (Unchecked), or "mixed" (Indeterminate); on iOS the indeterminate value is announced as "mixed" via accessibilityValue and on Android via stateDescription. The invalid state (Figma State=Error) is a persistent property, not a transient live region: fold it into the stop's state (accessibilityValue / stateDescription / aria-invalid) rather than announcing the error glyph as a standalone element, and surface the associated Helper / Error text via accessibilityHint / stateDescription / aria-describedby. When disabled (Figma State=Disabled) the checkbox is removed from the focus order entirely and exposes .notEnabled / isEnabled=false / aria-disabled=true. Do not stuff the accessible name with the value and helper text — each belongs on its dedicated property. Keep the single stop index stable across states so user gestures remain predictable. Platform merge differs only in mechanism: iOS uses accessibilityElement on the parent, Android uses mergeDescendants, Web uses <label for> and aria-describedby; the resulting single stop is the same across all three.

### State: rest

Default resting state (covers Figma State=Default and the transient Hover state, which share identical screen-reader semantics). Tri-state value is documented per Selection: Unchecked = aria-checked false, Checked = true, Indeterminate = mixed.

